<br>
Reluctantly, Ludria pushed open the heavy double doors that led to the council chambers. She knew her duty to her clan, the good Tremere always came first in her life, her clan was her life. It wasn't that she hated these meetings, just the unexpected ones, they never brought good news.<br>
<br>
As she entered the Hall, the doors swung shut with a deep thudding sound. Ludria pushed back the hood of her of her night black cloak and began to unhook the single clasp that held the cloak closed around her neck, the clasp was her clan's crest, worked in silver, it reminded her of her duty.<br>
<br>
As she continued to walk down the the length of the hall, the hard soles of her boots hitting marbled red tiles on the floor filled the air with muted sounds. The room was not built with acoustics in mind, but it served it's purpose. He cloak billowed behind her with the wind formed from the air escaping as the door closed.<br>
<br>
Had she been younger, she would have contemplated lowering the temperature in the room, but such pompous uses of her gifts would have been fruitless if not detrimental, she simply relied on her reputation to present herself.<br>
<br>
As she rounded her assigned chair at the table, she fully removed her cloak, and layed it folded neatly over the left arm of the chair before she sat down.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're looking well Trekondar. I'm glad to see you're still healthy, may we presume that time has been as kind to your mind as it has been to your body?&quot;<br>
<br>
She nodded in the direction of the other elder at the table.<br>
&quot;Ratri, its good to see you again as well&quot;.<br>
<br>
And so the games begin.<br>
<br>
